Explanation:

While the documents mention that Entebbe was the administrative capital of the British Uganda Protectorate from 1894 to 1962 (from file_path: /Users/stefanomarchesin/Research/fshami/Rag/docs/dbpedia_9218/re-ranker-msmarco/86.txt and /Users/stefanomarchesin/Research/fshami/Rag/docs/dbpedia_9218/re-ranker-msmarco/24.txt), they also mention that Kampala was the capital city of Uganda (from file_path: /Users/stefanomarchesin/Research/fshami/Rag/docs/dbpedia_9218/re-ranker-msmarco/86.txt and /Users/stefanomarchesin/Research/fshami/Rag/docs/dbpedia_9218/re-ranker-msmarco/24.txt). The Uganda Protectorate is not the same as modern-day Uganda, but Kampala was already the capital city of Uganda during the protectorate period. Therefore, Entebbe was not the capital of Uganda Protectorate in the sense that it was not the capital of the country that the protectorate was a part of.

llama3.1.reason: the Uganda Protectorate had limited internal autonomy with Buganda having its own autonomous administration, making Entebbe not necessarily the seat of government for the entire protectorate.

qwen2.5.reason: The Uganda Protectorate had its capital in Entebbe from 1894 to 1962, but the context also mentions that after independence in 1962, Entebbe became the seat of government for the newly independent Uganda. Therefore, it cannot be considered the capital of Uganda during the protectorate period alone; it was its capital during colonial rule.
